"{\"uid\": \"independent.co.uk-sport-olympics-team-gb-medals-olympics-2024-b2594582.html\", \"text\": \"Notifications can be managed in browser preferences.  Please refresh the page or navigate to another page on the site to be automatically logged inPlease refresh your browser to be logged in  Swipe for next article  How many medals did Team GB win at the Paris Olympics?  Removed from bookmarks  I would like to be emailed about offers, events and updates from The Independent. Read ourPrivacy notice  Team GBhave concluded a strongParis 2024with 65 medals, one more thanGreat Britainachieved at the TokyoOlympics, to finish sixth in the final medal table.  Officials had set a target of between 50 and 70 medals which was safely achieved as a number of big stars secured Olympic triumph, includingKeely Hodgkinson on the Stade de France track, Alex Yeein a dramatic men's triathlonand three crews on the water at Vaires-sur-Marne as therowers rebounded from a difficult time in Tokyo.  Great Britain did fall short of their tally of 22 golds from the last Summer Games, winning 14, with a series ofnear misses in the pooland in the athletics programme capping their top of the podium potential and ultimately meaning a drop of two places in the overall table.  Yet history was made as first medals werewon in climbing and artistic swimming, showcasing the pan-sport competitiveness of the British squad, while Emma Finucane was an individual standout,winning three medals at the velodrome.  Here is a day-by-day recap of all of Team GB's medals in Paris.  Anna Henderson(cycling, women's road time trial) \\ud83e\\udd48  Yasmin Harper,Scarlett Mew Jensen(diving, women's 3m synchronized springboard) \\ud83e\\udd49  Adam Peaty(swimming, men's 100 metre breaststroke) \\ud83e\\udd48  Kimberley Woods(canoeing, women's slalom K-1)\\ud83e\\udd49  Ros Canter, Laura Collett, Tom McEwen(equestrian, team eventing)\\ud83e\\udd47  Tom Pidcock(cycling, men's cross-country) \\ud83e\\udd47  Tom Daley, Noah Williams(diving, men's synchronized 10m platform) \\ud83e\\udd48  Adam Burgess(canoeing, men's slalom C-1)\\ud83e\\udd48  Matt Richards(swimming, men's 200m freestyle)\\ud83e\\udd48  Laura Collett(equestrian, individual eventing) \\ud83e\\udd49  Nathan Hales(shooting, men's trap) \\ud83e\\udd47  Matt Richards,Duncan Scott,Tom Dean,James Guy,Kieran Bird,Jack McMillan(swimming, men's 4x200m freestyle relay) \\ud83e\\udd47  Alex Yee(triathlon, men's race) \\ud83e\\udd47  Lauren Henry,Hannah Scott,Lola Anderson,Georgie Brayshaw(rowing, women's quadruple sculls) \\ud83e\\udd47  Kieran Reilly(freestyle BMX, men's park final) \\ud83e\\udd48  Beth Potter(triathlon, women's race)\\ud83e\\udd49  Andrea Spendolini-Sirieix,Lois Toulson(diving, women's 10m synchronized platform) \\ud83e\\udd49  Mathilda Hodgkins-Byrne, Rebecca Wilde(rowing, women's double sculls)\\ud83e\\udd49  Helen Glover, Esme Booth, Sam Redgrave, Rebecca Shorten(rowing, women's four)\\ud83e\\udd48  Oliver Wilkes, David Ambler, Matt Aldridge, Freddie Davidson(rowing, men's four)\\ud83e\\udd49  Oliver Wynne-Griffith, Tom George(rowing, men's pair)\\ud83e\\udd48  Jack Laugher, Anthony Harding(diving, men's 3m synchronized springboard)\\ud83e\\udd49  Emily Craig, Imogen Grant(rowing, women's lightweight double sculls)\\ud83e\\udd47  Bryony Page(gymnastics, women's trampoline)\\ud83e\\udd47  Scott Brash, Ben Maher, Harry Charles(equestrian, team jumping)\\ud83e\\udd47  Ben Proud(swimming, men's 50m freestyle) \\ud83e\\udd48  Duncan Scott(swimming, men/s 200m medley) \\ud83e\\udd48  Heidi Long, Rowan McKellar, Holly Dunford, Emily Ford, Lauren Irwin, Eve Stewart, Hattie Taylor, Annie Campbell-Orde, Henry Fieldman [cox](rowing, women's eight) \\ud83e\\udd49  Sholto Carnegie, Rory Gibbs, Morgan Bolding, Jacob Dawson, Charlie Elwes, Tom Digby, James Rudkin, Tom Ford and Harry Brightmore [cox](rowing, men's eight) \\ud83e\\udd47  Emma Wilson(sailing, women's IQFoil) \\ud83e\\udd49  Lottie Fry,Carl Hester,Becki Mood